{"@context": "http://schema.org", "@type": "MedicalWebPage", "name": "Hives", "copyrightHolder": {"name": "Crown Copyright", "@type": "Organization"}, "license": "https://developer.api.nhs.uk/terms", "author": {"url": "https://www.nhs.uk", "logo": "https://www.nhs.uk/nhscwebservices/documents/logo1.jpg", "email": "nhswebsite.servicedesk@nhs.net", "@type": "Organization", "name": "NHS website"}, "about": {"@type": "MedicalCondition", "name": "Hives", "alternateName": []}, "description": "Urticaria – also known as hives, weals, welts or nettle rash – is a raised, itchy rash that appears on the skin. It may appear on one part of the body or be spread across large areas.", "url": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/hives/", "lastReviewed": ["2018-02-06T00:00:00+00:00", "2021-02-06T00:00:00+00:00"], "breadcrumb": {"@context": "http://schema.org", "@type": "BreadcrumbList", "itemListElement": [{"@type": "ListItem", "position": 0, "item": {"@id": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/", "name": "Health A to Z", "genre": "condition"}}, {"@type": "ListItem", "position": 1, "item": {"@id": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/hives/", "name": "Hives", "genre": "condition"}}]}, "dateModified": "2020-08-12T07:40:29+00:00", "genre": "condition", "hasPart": [{"@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "overview", "url": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/hives/#overview", "description": "Hives is an itchy, raised rash usually caused by a reaction to things like food, pollen, insect bites or chemicals.", "text": "<p>The main symptom of hives is a blotchy, raised red rash. It's often very itchy.</p><p>You can usually treat hives with antihistamines from a pharmacy. If it does not get better, a GP may prescribe steroids or stronger antihistamines.</p>"}, {"@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "symptoms", "url": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/hives/#symptoms", "description": "The main symptom of hives is a blotchy, raised red rash. It's often very itchy.", "text": "    <p><img  alt="Hives 1" height="426" src="https://assets.nhs.uk/nhsuk-cms/images/C0269180-Urticaria-SPL.width-640.jpg" width="640" alt="Red, raised skin on a leg"/><br/>Hives can look like red, raised patches.</p>    <p><img  alt="Hives 2" height="426" src="https://assets.nhs.uk/nhsuk-cms/images/GDR5M4.width-640.jpg" width="640" alt="Red spots on a leg"/><br/>The rash can also be red spots.</p><p>Hives can be different sizes and shapes, and appear anywhere on the body in both adults and children.</p><p>The rash is often itchy and sometimes feels like it's stinging or burning.</p>", "title": "Check if you have hives"}, {"@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "self_care", "url": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/hives/#self-care", "description": "You can usually treat hives with antihistamines from a pharmacy. If it does not get better, a GP may prescribe steroids or stronger antihistamines.", "text": "<p>Your pharmacist can give you advice about <a href="https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/antihistamines/">antihistamine tablets</a> to bring down your hives rash.</p><p>Tell your pharmacist if you have a long-term condition – you might not be able to take antihistamines.</p><p>They also may not be suitable for young children.</p>", "title": "A pharmacist can help with hives"}, {"@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "treatments_overview", "url": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/hives/#treatments-summary", "description": "You can usually treat hives with antihistamines from a pharmacy. If it does not get better, a GP may prescribe steroids or stronger antihistamines.", "text": "", "title": ""}, {"@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "other_treatments", "url": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/hives/#treatments-other", "description": "You can usually treat hives with antihistamines from a pharmacy. If it does not get better, a GP may prescribe steroids or stronger antihistamines.", "text": "<p>Your GP may prescribe <a href="https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/steroids/">corticosteroids</a>, menthol cream or stronger antihistamines.</p><p>If your hives do not go away with treatment, you may be referred to a skin specialist (dermatologist).</p>", "title": "Treatment for hives from a GP"}], "relatedLink": [{"@type": "LinkRole", "url": "https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/hives/", "linkRelationship": "Navigation", "position": 0, "name": "Hives"}], "keywords": [], "mainEntityOfPage": [{"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 0, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "", "text": "", "mainEntityOfPage": [{"position": 0, "identifier": "1", "text": "<p><b>Hives rashes usually settle down within a few minutes to a few days. You can often treat hives yourself.</b></p>", "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "markdown"}]}, {"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 1, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "Check if you have hives", "text": "Symptoms", "mainEntityOfPage": [{"position": 0, "identifier": "13", "@type": "ImageObject", "name": "Red, raised skin on a leg", "url": "https://assets.nhs.uk/nhsuk-cms/images/C0269180-Urticaria-SPL.max-600x600.jpg", "provider": "Science Photo Library", "license": "DR P. MARAZZI/SCIENCE PHOTO LIBRARY

https://www.sciencephoto.com/media/694159/view", "datePublished": "2017-06-21T13:47:48+00:00", "keywords": []}, {"position": 2, "identifier": "1", "text": "<p>Hives can be different sizes and shapes, and appear anywhere on the body in both adults and children.</p><p>The rash is often itchy and sometimes feels like it&#x27;s stinging or burning.</p>", "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "markdown"}]}, {"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 2, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "", "text": "", "mainEntityOfPage": [{"position": 0, "identifier": "1", "text": "<h3>If you&#x27;re not sure it&#x27;s hives</h3><p>Look at other <a href="https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/rashes-babies-and-children/">rashes in babies and children</a>.</p>", "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "markdown"}]}, {"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 3, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "A pharmacist can help with hives", "text": "How a pharmacist can help", "mainEntityOfPage": [{"position": 0, "identifier": "1", "text": "<p>Your pharmacist can give you advice about <a href="https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/antihistamines/">antihistamine tablets</a> to bring down your hives rash.</p><p>Tell your pharmacist if you have a long-term condition – you might not be able to take antihistamines.</p><p>They also may not be suitable for young children.</p>", "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "markdown"}]}, {"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 4, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "", "text": "", "mainEntityOfPage": [{"position": 0, "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "Find a service", "identifier": "2", "text": "<p><a href="https://www.nhs.uk/service-search/find-a-pharmacy/">Find a pharmacy</a></p>
"}]}, {"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 5, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "", "text": "When to get medical help", "mainEntityOfPage": [{"position": 0, "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "Primary care", "identifier": "5", "text": "<h3>See a GP if:</h3><div class="block-richtext"><ul><li>the symptoms do not improve after 2 days</li><li>you&#x27;re worried about your child&#x27;s hives</li><li>the rash is spreading</li><li>your hives keep coming back – you may be allergic to something</li><li>you also have a high temperature and feel generally unwell</li><li>you also have swelling under the skin – this might be <a href="https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/angioedema/">angioedema</a></li></ul></div>"}, {"position": 1, "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "Emergency", "identifier": "5", "text": "<h3>Go to A&E or call 999 if you have:</h3><div class="block-richtext"><ul><li>difficulty breathing</li><li>difficulty swallowing</li><li>dizziness or fainting</li><li>nausea or vomiting</li><li>an increased heart rate</li><li>rapid and severe swelling of the face, mouth or throat</li></ul><p>These could be signs of a severe allergic reaction, such as <a href="https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/anaphylaxis/">anaphylactic shock</a>.</p></div>"}]}, {"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 6, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "", "text": "", "mainEntityOfPage": []}, {"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 7, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "Treatment for hives from a GP", "text": "Treatment from a GP", "mainEntityOfPage": [{"position": 0, "identifier": "1", "text": "<p>Your GP may prescribe <a href="https://api.nhs.uk/conditions/steroids/">corticosteroids</a>, menthol cream or stronger antihistamines.</p><p>If your hives do not go away with treatment, you may be referred to a skin specialist (dermatologist).</p>", "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "markdown"}]}, {"identifier": "0", "name": "section heading", "position": 8, "@type": "WebPageElement", "headline": "", "text": "Causes and prevention", "mainEntityOfPage": [{"position": 0, "identifier": "1", "text": "<h2>You cannot always prevent hives</h2><p>Hives occur when something causes high levels of histamine and other chemicals to be released in the skin. This is known as a trigger.</p><p>Triggers can include:</p><ul><li>food</li><li>pollen and plants</li><li>insect bites and stings</li><li>chemicals</li><li>latex</li><li>dust mites</li><li>heat – work and sleep in a cool room and wear loose, lightweight clothes</li><li>sunlight, exercise or water</li><li>medicines – speak to a GP if you have an allergic reaction</li><li>infections</li><li>emotional stress</li></ul>", "@type": "WebPageElement", "name": "markdown"}]}]}
